  "description": {
    "en": "Learn Python threading — Thread creation, Lock for synchronization, the GIL explained, and when threads actually help (I/O-bound tasks).",
    "ta": "Python threading — Thread உருவாக்கம், synchronization-க்கு Lock, GIL விளக்கம், threads உண்மையில் எப்போது உதவும் (I/O-bound tasks)."
  },
  "xp_reward": 70,
  "story_variants": {
    "en": "## Vaathiyaar's Assembly Line Workers\n\nVaathiyaar has workers on an assembly line. \"Each worker is a **thread** — they share the same workspace (memory). But Python has a rule: only ONE worker can use the tool bench (CPU) at a time. That's the **GIL** (Global Interpreter Lock)!\"\n\n### Threading Concepts\n\n| Concept | Meaning |\n|---------|----------|\n| Thread | A separate flow of execution |\n| GIL | Only one thread runs Python code at a time |\n| Lock | Prevents two threads from modifying shared data simultaneously |\n| I/O-bound | Tasks that wait for network, disk, etc. |\n| CPU-bound | Tasks that do heavy computation |\n\n### When to Use Threads\n\n```\nI/O-bound (waiting) -> Use threads or async\nCPU-bound (computing) -> Use multiprocessing\n```\n\n> **Key Concept:** The GIL means threads DON'T speed up CPU-bound Python code. But they're perfect for I/O-bound tasks (downloading files, reading databases) because the GIL is released during I/O waits."
  },
